## 3. Install Node.js, Git & Expo CLI

> 🔗 **Official Reference:** https://docs.expo.dev/get-started/installation/

### Step 3.1 — Install Node.js

**Recommended: Use nvm (Node Version Manager)**

```bash
# macOS / Linux
curl -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvm-sh/nvm/v0.39.7/install.sh | bash
source ~/.bashrc   # or ~/.zshrc on macOS

# Install and use Node 20 LTS
nvm install 20
nvm use 20
nvm alias default 20

# Verify
node --version   # v20.x.x
npm --version    # 10.x.x
```

**Windows — Use nvm-windows:**
```powershell
# Download installer from:
# https://github.com/coreybutler/nvm-windows/releases
nvm install 20.0.0
nvm use 20.0.0
```

**Direct Download (Alternative):**
- Official installer: https://nodejs.org/en/download

### Step 3.2 — Install Git

```bash
# macOS
brew install git

# Ubuntu/Debian
sudo apt install git

# Windows: https://git-scm.com/download/win

# Verify
git --version
```

### Step 3.3 — Expo CLI

Expo CLI is now included via **npx**. No global install required:

```bash
# Always use latest via npx (recommended)
npx expo --version

# OR install globally (optional)
npm install -g expo-cli
expo --version
```

> ⚠️ **Important:** The old `expo-cli` global package is deprecated. Use `npx expo` or install `@expo/cli` via:
> ```bash
> npm install -g @expo/cli
> ```
> 🔗 https://docs.expo.dev/more/expo-cli/

### Step 3.4 — Install EAS CLI

```bash
# Install globally (required for builds)
npm install -g eas-cli

# Verify
eas --version   # 10.x.x or higher
```
> 🔗 https://docs.expo.dev/eas-update/getting-started/

